voice_to_text: A drag performer in Idaho was just awarded $1.1 million in a defamation suit against the far right blogger hey, I'm Trav, I report on the queer economy. And it all stems from defamatory post that summer Bush now published to her blog and to Facebook page in 2022 claiming that drag artist Eric Posey, who performs under the drag name Mona Lisa Million, exposed himself to a crowd that included children at a 2022 Pride event in Corda Lane, Idaho. Bushnail's deceitful post included a doctored video of Posey with a blurred spot that she erroneously claimed covered his, quote unquote, fully exposed genitals. But the truth is that the unedited video showed that Posey was clothed and that there was no indecent exposure. Nonetheless, these fraudulent claims LED to Posey receiving death threats and harassment, and the edited images became fodder for the nationwide right wing movement against drag over the past couple of years. But on Friday, it took a jury only three and a/2 hours to unanimously find that summer Bushnell not only defamed Eric Posey with her post, but did so intentionally. The jurors awarded Posey $926,000 in compensatory damages for defamation and an additional $250,000 in punitive damages because Posie proved that Bush now knew her allegations were false when she made them, or that she made them with reckless disregard for the truth. This is the second case this year where a drag performer successfully sued someone for defaming them. The first was in January when Drag Race UK star Crystal won a high profile libel suit against British actor and conservative activist Lawrence Fox. But the case in Idaho represents what I think is a breakthrough moment in the fight against anti drag fervor in the US. First we have to consider the context of where this case took place. Court Elaine, Idaho is notorious for being a Pacific Northwest hotbed of white supremacist racism, homophobia, anti semitism, Islamophobia and other forms of bigotry. Now, of course, everyone who lives in court Elaine is not a card carrying member of the Aryan Nation. But the fact that a jury of peers in a region with such an infamous reputation delivered such a crushing verdict against the right wing blogger in support of a black queer drag queen says a lot. And what I think it means is that people are just tired of right wing culture wars. There has been a record number of anti LGBTQ legislation introduced in state legislatures this year, but hardly any have passed. And this could be a cautiously optimistic sign that anti LGBTQ momentum is actually decreasing. And I think that's because the vast majority of Americans have other things on their mind. People are concerned about inflation in the economy, abortion access, immigration, the Supreme Court, democracy, and the ongoing genocides and atrocities happening across the globe. Even folks that are not our allies have other things to worry about than Drag Queens Story Hour. voice_to_text: An apology is not necessarily accountability, and many times we accept someone's apology because we want reconciliation in the relationship so badly, or we want the relationship to match an image in our mind. We can accept apologies without demanding accountability, but accepting an apology too quickly doesn't always mean that the other person is accountable. And not accepting an apology quickly doesn't mean that you're immature or holding onto an offense. An apology must be coupled with accountability, and accountability is the action of the words I apologize. I want to see your apology carried out by the way that you walk and the way that you live. So I hear your apology, but I pay attention to your walk after the apology, because I'm sorry can't heal my heart. I'm sorry can't heal the wound. I'm sorry can't heal the offense. But your change behavior can begin the process. So if you don't have change behavior, you can keep the apology.

voice_to_text: Hi, everybody. I wanna do a quick video on how to help a woman in your life who discloses to you that she's been abused by her partner. So a couple of quick things that aren't helpful. Don't say to her, why didn't you tell me sooner? Okay? This puts guilt on her. It makes this about you now instead of what she's going through. And the reality of the situation is there are many complicated reasons why she didn't tell you. Most of them have to do with fear. And usually none of them have to do with how much she loves her trust you. Okay, the second thing that's not helpful is to say, why did you stay for so long? Okay? That puts judgment and shame on her instead of on her abuser for abusing her. And the reality of the situation, again, is there. There are many complicated reasons why she stayed. One of them is probably because he undermined her ability to trust herself. So what I want you to do instead to help her is to help bolster her sense of confidence. Say things to her like, I believe that you are smart and capable and strong and able to make good decisions for yourself. I have confidence in your abilities. You can figure this out. And I'm here for you. Okay? And I want you also just to offer a place of safety for her. How can I help? What can I do? To help you in the situation. How can I support you? How can I help you feel safe? Okay, anything that offers her safety and a safe haven is going to be helpful to her. So support, increasing confidence and offering safety, that those are the best things that you can do for her.
